JDBC

    For the application to connect to the DB there are 7 steps to be followed 

    Steps:
    1. Import packages in java
    2. Load Driver
        Driver is provided by the RDBMS - each one can be diff
        from Java 6 this is optional -> JVM auto-loads the driver
        2.1. Register the driver 
    3. Establish connection
            Connection con = DriverManager.getConnection(url, user, password);
                url -> rdbms name, database name, local host - port no
            Statement stmt = con.createStatement();
                There are other class similar to Statement, we can use them also
                Statement is not secure -> prone to SQL injection i.e 
                    in place of a number you can enter an sql query
                PreparedStatemnt is better option because it doesn't allow an SL query in place of a number
    5. Execute Statement
            ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM students");
                The executeQuery() returns a ResultSet
                here the 'rs' is like a pointer to the result 
    6. Process Results
    7. Close the connection
            stmt.close();
            con.close();

SPRING JDBC:

Spring simplifies JDBC connection with the help of JDBCTemplate
JDBCTemplate -> JDBC technology +  Template Design Pattern
This template carries all the boiler plate code and reduces developers work
    JDBCTemplate depends on DataSource [This is an interface]
    DriverManagerDataSource is an implementation calss and we have to create a bean for this class and inject it to JDBCTemplate

    The DriverManagerDataSource takes 4 parameters and is responsible for giving the DB connection

Need for Spring JDBC when we can connect through normal JDBC:
    1. Optimization
        For every request a new connection is established 
        InstDataSource provides connection pooling
    2. Reduce Boilerplate code

What is JdbcTemplate?
    JdbcTemplate is a Spring Framework class used to interact with databases easily.
    It simplifies JDBC by:

    Removing boilerplate code
    Handling connection open and close
    Handling SQL exceptions internally

    Package name:
    org.springframework.jdbc.core.JdbcTemplate

Why use JdbcTemplate?
    Problems with normal JDBC:
        Too much code
        Manual connection handling
        Manual exception handling
    
    JdbcTemplate advantages:
        Less code
        Easy database operations
        No manual connection management
        Cleaner and readable code

    Conclusion:
    JdbcTemplate makes JDBC simple.

When to use JdbcTemplate?
    Use JdbcTemplate when:
        You are using Spring
        You want simple database operations
        You do not want complex ORM frameworks

    Required dependency (Maven)
        <dependency>
            <groupid>org.springframework.boot</groupid>
            <artifactid>spring-boot-starter-jdbc</artifactid>
        </dependency>


Database configuration (application.properties)

    spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/testdb
    spring.datasource.username=root
    spring.datasource.password=root
    spring.datasource.driver-class-name=com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver


Creating JdbcTemplate object
    @Autowired
    private JdbcTemplate jdbcTemplate;
    Spring automatically creates and injects JdbcTemplate.


Insert operation example
    SQL:
        INSERT INTO student VALUES (1, 'Lahari');
        Java code:
        String sql = "INSERT INTO student VALUES (?, ?)";
        int result = jdbcTemplate.update(sql, 1, "Lahari");
        System.out.println("Rows inserted: " + result);
        Note:
        update() method is used for INSERT, UPDATE and DELETE.


Update operation example
    String sql = "UPDATE student SET name=? WHERE id=?";
    jdbcTemplate.update(sql, "Anu", 1);


Delete operation example
    String sql = "DELETE FROM student WHERE id=?";
    jdbcTemplate.update(sql, 1);


Read single value example (COUNT)
    String sql = "SELECT COUNT(*) FROM student";
    int count = jdbcTemplate.queryForObject(sql, Integer.class);
    System.out.println(count);


Read single row example
    String sql = "SELECT name FROM student WHERE id=?";
    String name = jdbcTemplate.queryForObject(sql, String.class, 1);
    System.out.println(name);


Read multiple rows example
    String sql = "SELECT * FROM student";
    List<student> students = jdbcTemplate.query(
        sql,
            (rs, rowNum) -> new Student(
            rs.getInt("id"),
            rs.getString("name")
        )
    );</student>


Student class
    public class Student {
        private int id;
        private String name;

        public Student(int id, String name) {
            this.id = id;
            this.name = name;
        }

        public int getId() {
            return id;
        }

        public String getName() {
            return name;
        }

    }

Important JdbcTemplate methods
    update() – for INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE
    queryForObject() – for single row or single value
    query() – for multiple rows
